---
import ProposalLayout from '../../../layouts/ProposalLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "WebPage",
  "name": "The Story Behind the Pitch — Barry Grottis",
  "description": "15 years of digital marketing, product creation, and relentless iteration — told in full."
};
---

<ProposalLayout
  title="The Story Behind the Pitch — Barry Grottis"
  description="15 years of digital marketing, product creation, and relentless iteration. The full story."
  schema={schema}
>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="pt-24 md:pt-32 pb-12 md:pb-16 px-6">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
      <div class="inline-block bg-terracotta/10 text-terracotta-dark text-xs px-4 py-2 rounded-full font-semibold mb-6 tracking-wide uppercase">
        The Full Story
      </div>
      <h1 class="proposal-hero-title mb-6">
        I Built an Entire Product<br class="hidden sm:block"/> as My Application.<br class="hidden sm:block"/> <span class="text-sage">Here's Why.</span>
      </h1>
      <p class="text-lg md:text-xl text-text-secondary max-w-2xl mx-auto leading-relaxed mb-8">
        Most people send a PDF. I spent weeks building a full product proposal, market analysis, competitive landscape, and financial model — because that's what I'd do if I already had the job.
      </p>

      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-center justify-center gap-4 sm:gap-6 pt-6 border-t border-border">
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
          <div class="w-16 h-16 rounded-full border-3 border-sage overflow-hidden shadow-sm mb-2" style="border-width:3px;">
            <img src="/images/team/barry-profile.png" alt="Barry Grottis" class="w-full h-full object-cover" />
          </div>
          <span class="font-bold text-text-primary text-sm">Barry Grottis</span>
          <span class="text-xs text-text-secondary">The Orchestrator</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex flex-col items-center">
          <div class="w-16 h-16 rounded-full border-3 border-terracotta overflow-hidden shadow-sm bg-terracotta/10 flex items-center justify-center mb-2" style="border-width:3px;">
            <img src="/images/team/al-roberts-avatar.svg" alt="AL. Roborts" class="w-11 h-11 object-contain" />
          </div>
          <span class="font-bold text-text-primary text-sm">AL. Roborts</span>
          <span class="text-xs text-text-secondary">The Heavy Lifter</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PROLOGUE: BORN READY -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Prologue</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">Born Ready — Zimbabwe</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          I was born in Zimbabwe, Africa. My father worked in the mines, and we moved constantly — new towns, new schools, new people. Before I was ten, I'd already learned the most useful skill of my life: <strong>how to adapt fast.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          Zimbabwe in the eighties and nineties was a place where the outdoors wasn't a lifestyle choice — it was just life. I grew up hunting snakes, fighting warthogs, and having my barbecue stolen off my plate by hawks. All of that is true. I loved every minute of it. Nature, the bush, the garden — that's where I felt most alive.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sport was the other constant. I played rugby, track and field, cricket — anything competitive. I was naturally athletic, but more importantly, I was <em>always training</em>. That instinct — to stay prepared, to be ready for whatever game shows up — became the rhythm of my entire life. It just took me a while to realize it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 1: THE SPARK -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 1</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The Spark — 2011</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          It started with a simple promise: <em>"Send an email. Make money."</em>
        </p>
        <p>
          I'd just finished studying health, fitness, and nutrition — genuinely passionate about the science of how the human body works. Then I stumbled across an information product about email marketing and YouTube marketing, and something clicked. Not about the product itself, but about the <em>mechanism</em>. The idea that you could build a system, put it in front of the right people, and revenue could follow — that hooked me instantly.
        </p>
        <p>
          The method was straightforward: build an affiliate landing page that captured emails, then send those leads to a ClickBank offer. My first product was in the health and fitness niche — a natural fit given my background. The product was called <strong>The Truth About Abs</strong> by Mike Geary, and at the time, it was the <strong>number one selling information product on ClickBank for an entire year</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          I learned website design. I learned how to build opt-in pages with lead capture forms. I studied the mechanics of a funnel before I even knew that's what it was called. And then I waited.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 2: THE FIRST DOLLAR -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 2</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The First Dollar</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          It took a full year.
        </p>
        <p>
          Twelve months of building, tweaking, optimizing, and wondering if any of this was real. Then one day — a sale. My first commission as an affiliate marketer. I don't remember the exact amount, but I remember the feeling. It was electric. That single notification proved something I'd suspected but couldn't confirm: <strong>this system works.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I was hooked.
        </p>
        <p>
          The next decade became a relentless pursuit of that feeling — trying to replicate it, scale it, and turn it into something sustainable. Some campaigns worked. Most didn't. But every single one taught me something that a textbook never could.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 3: THE SEO RABBIT HOLE -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 3</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The SEO Rabbit Hole</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          My primary avenue for getting sales was paid ads — particularly Microsoft Ads (then Bing Ads). They were more lenient with affiliate marketers than Google, which made them the natural choice for someone working with a tight budget.
        </p>
        <p>
          But I learned an important lesson early: <strong>with a small budget, you're always choosing between paid ads and organic growth.</strong> You can't do both well. So I started reading heavily into SEO, building websites optimized for search, and playing the long game.
        </p>
        <p>
          Timing, as it turned out, was not on my side. I entered the SEO world right after Google's <strong>Panda and Penguin updates</strong> — the updates that wiped out the affiliate gold rush. Before those updates, people were ranking affiliate pages for health and fitness products on Google with almost reckless abandon. It had been a gold mine. By the time I arrived, the mine was closed.
        </p>
        <p>
          So I adapted. I learned to use alternative platforms — Bing Ads, cost-per-view networks, and various other channels that were still friendly to affiliate marketing. I stayed in the health and fitness niche, testing different products, different angles, different traffic sources. The core strategy was always paid ads for immediate results, SEO for long-term compounding.
        </p>
        <p>
          That experience — finding the organic channels others ignored, thinking creatively about distribution instead of just buying traffic — it's the same mindset Cupla is looking for. <strong>Not "more content." Better angles. Smarter channels.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 4: PRODUCT #1 -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-terracotta-dark bg-terracotta/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 4</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">Product #1 — The Hard Lesson</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          Inspired by the success of The Truth About Abs, I decided to create my own product. I spent the better part of a year writing a comprehensive exercise and nutrition eBook. My thinking was simple: I'd studied this stuff, I understood the science, I could bring my own unique angle, and I could create something similar to what was already working.
        </p>
        <p>
          What I <em>didn't</em> understand was <strong>market fit</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          I thought a good product was enough. Write a solid eBook, put it out there, and it would sell. The reality was far more brutal. Without marketing — without a clear understanding of <em>who</em> the product was for and <em>how</em> to reach them — even the best product in the world gathers dust.
        </p>
        <p>
          That lesson sent me back into affiliate marketing and SEO with renewed focus. But the desire to create something of my own never went away. It just waited for the right moment.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 5: PRODUCT #2 -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-terracotta-dark bg-terracotta/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 5</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">Product #2 — The Achilles Heel</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          In 2014, while completing my second course in health, fitness, and nutrition, I suffered an <strong>Achilles rupture</strong>. The rehabilitation process gave me an idea: a recovery eBook focused on tendinitis. I'd seen products in the market addressing shin splints, back pain, and soreness — recovery-type products that seemed to be gaining traction.
        </p>
        <p>
          I spent another year creating a comprehensive eBook. I really focused on launching it solidly on ClickBank, convinced that personal experience plus market demand was the winning formula.
        </p>
        <p>
          It wasn't.
        </p>
        <p>
          The hard truth: <strong>just because I thought it was a good idea didn't make it market fit.</strong> The niche was small. Existing products had minimal traction. The best performers were doing very small numbers. I'd built something I believed in, but the market didn't care about belief — it cared about demand, positioning, and timing.
        </p>
        <p>
          Between 2014 and 2020, I focused primarily on affiliate marketing, SEO, and paid ads — always building with SEO as the long-term strategy, occasionally dabbling in paid traffic when the budget allowed.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 6: THE OFFLINE EXPERIMENT -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 6</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The Offline Experiment</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          Somewhere along the way, I tried something completely different. I placed an ad in a newspaper — targeting older demographics interested in alternative health remedies like apple cider vinegar, honey, and lemon. The ad directed them to call a special hotline number and leave their details.
        </p>
        <p>
          I would then ship them a printed pamphlet — basically an eBook I'd had printed — which served as a long-form sales pitch for a physical supplement product I was drop-shipping. There was a small fee that covered the cost of printing and shipping.
        </p>
        <p>
          I made exactly <strong>two sales</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          One came from someone who read the pamphlet and bought online. The other? <em>The person at the printing press</em> read the pamphlet, thought it was compelling, and bought some tablets on the spot.
        </p>
        <p>
          That second sale — from the printer — was unintentional market validation. It proved the copy worked. The <em>delivery</em> was the problem. Customer acquisition cost far exceeded the revenue, making it a net-negative campaign.
        </p>
        <p>
          But it kept me in the direct response marketing world, and it taught me something invaluable: <strong>good copy sells. The channel is just the vehicle.</strong> I'd spend the next decade learning every channel I could find.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 7: PRODUCT #3 -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-terracotta-dark bg-terracotta/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 7</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">Product #3 — The Carb Insight</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          By 2019–2020, I was disillusioned with the affiliate marketing world. Many of the products felt scammy — they didn't deliver real value to real people. I wanted to create something better.
        </p>
        <p>
          I wrote my third eBook: <strong>The 28-Day Carb Challenge</strong>. This time I did things differently. I wrote it fast. I leaned into a product concept that was already proven — carb-based fat loss — but with a unique spin: what if you could eat bread, carbs, and sugar and still lose weight?
        </p>
        <p>
          The research was grounded in real science. The Rice Diet by Walter Kempner, a peer-reviewed study from the 1940s with remarkable results. Modern interpretations by Nathan Pritikin and Dr. John McDougall, who advocated high-carb eating from a vegan perspective. Nobody had branded it as a "high-carb challenge." I saw the gap and moved.
        </p>
        <p>
          But the real breakthrough wasn't the diet. It was the <strong>sales mechanism</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          I offered a free eBook as an opt-in. After signing up, visitors were redirected to a <strong>one-time offer</strong> — the exact same sales page, but pitching the full paid program instead of the free eBook. Same wording. Same design. Same value proposition, just bigger.
        </p>
        <p>
          And here's what happened: <strong>people signed up for the free eBook, saw the paid offer on the very next page, and bought it — before they'd even read the free one.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          That insight was worth more than any single sale. When people are hot — when they've just raised their hand and said "yes, I want this" — if you immediately offer them a bigger version of the same thing with added value, they'll take it. Heat equals conversion. The lesson: <strong>strike when the iron is hot, and make the next step obvious.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 8: THE AI PIVOT -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 8</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The AI Pivot</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          In the early 2020s, I was introduced to ChatGPT. I immediately started thinking about how to use it to create content — just like everyone else at the time. But I also saw something deeper: <strong>a new market was forming, and I wanted to be ahead of it.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I devoured YouTube videos on AI. I followed the creators who were pushing the boundaries. My initial idea was practical — use AI to help build websites, particularly the WordPress sites I'd been running since 2014.
        </p>
        <p>
          As I explored, I discovered tools like n8n and Flowise for automation. I started imagining how much of the WordPress build process I could automate. The more I learned, the more I saw the potential for AI to not just assist, but to fundamentally change how digital products are created and marketed.
        </p>
        <p>
          This wasn't a hobby interest. This was a strategic pivot — the same pattern I'd followed my whole career: see the shift early, move before the crowd, learn by doing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 9: THE ACCELERATION -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 9</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The Acceleration — 2026</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          At the start of 2026, everything accelerated.
        </p>
        <p>
          I started using AI assistants through tools like OpenCode, Roo Code, and Kilo Code inside VS Code, exploring how to integrate AI into the website building process. I learned to connect my AI system to Docker to initialize WordPress sites. I learned the limitations — and the possibilities.
        </p>
        <p>
          I was getting familiar with the AI ecosystem as it was exploding: how models work, how harnesses operate, AI coding systems, image generation, video generation. The entire landscape was shifting under everyone's feet, and I was riding the wave.
        </p>
        <p>
          Then in March, I made a decision that changed everything. <strong>I stepped outside WordPress entirely.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I started building on Cloudflare — using their infrastructure because it connected so seamlessly with AI agents and could execute almost everything autonomously. The design quality was immediately superior. The setup was faster. The automation was deeper.
        </p>
        <p>
          Within weeks, I'd developed a system for building fully SEO-optimized websites with custom designs and AI-generated images — completed in <strong>a couple of hours</strong>. Sometimes less.
        </p>
        <p>
          That led to a new business: building websites for local service-based businesses who were either lacking a web presence or stuck with a bad one. I started approaching potential clients, looking for opportunities.
        </p>
        <p>
          I was going past the ChatGPT chat window. Into analytics tools, MCPs, lightweight automation. Not because anyone told me to — because I'm <em>technically curious</em>. That's just how I'm wired.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 10: THE RECURRING DREAM -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-sage bg-sage/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 10</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The Recurring Dream</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          I have this dream. It comes back, again and again.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm back on the rugby field. Big tournament. Crowd's roaring. I'm supposed to be ready — I always was ready. I played provincial rugby in Zimbabwe, and then again in New Zealand when I came here. I was <em>always</em> training back then. Always in shape. Always prepared for the next game, the next opportunity.
        </p>
        <p>
          But in the dream, I haven't trained in years. The game is happening <em>right now</em>, and I can feel it — my body isn't ready. My mind isn't ready. I'm standing on the field knowing I should have been preparing for this moment, and I wasn't.
        </p>
        <p>
          It's the most unsettling feeling I've ever had in a dream. And it's <em>always</em> the same.
        </p>
        <p>
          Here's what I've come to understand about that dream: <strong>it was never about rugby.</strong> It was about readiness. About staying in shape for whatever game shows up next. And for the last fifteen years — through every failed product, every SEO campaign, every sales letter I handwritten to study copywriting, every book on direct response I devoured, every late night learning AI systems — <strong>I've been training.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I just didn't know what game I was training for. Until now.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPTER 11: THE MOMENT -->
  <section class="spoke-section-alt">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <span class="text-xs font-semibold text-terracotta-dark bg-terracotta/10 px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Chapter 11</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="proposal-section-title">The Moment</h2>
      <div class="prose-story">
        <p>
          I was scrolling through SEEK, looking for potential businesses to approach for my website service, when I saw it.
        </p>
        <p>
          A job listing from Cupla. <strong>Growth Marketer.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I've never liked looking at job listings. They've always felt depressing — rigid, corporate, soulless. But this one was different. It read like it was written <em>for</em> me. Organic growth thinking. Creative distribution. SEO as a creative discipline, not a checkbox. Hands-on doer. Technically curious past the default output. Finding the angle nobody else sees.
        </p>
        <p>
          It stopped me cold. Everything I'd been learning and doing for 15 years — the marketing, the product development, the SEO, the direct response copywriting, the AI automation, the dozens of copywriting books, the handwritten sales letters, the experiments in organic and paid channels — it all converged on that single job description.
        </p>
        <p>
          I went into instant marketing mode.
        </p>
        <p>
          Not "update my resume" mode. Not "write a cover letter" mode. <em>Marketing</em> mode. The same instinct that kicked in when I saw The Truth About Abs, when I identified the carb diet gap, when I realized AI could automate website builds — that same instinct said: <strong>find the unique angle. Build something nobody else would build. Make it impossible to ignore.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          This isn't just a job to me. It's an entrepreneurial role inside a company that's already winning — top 1% of revenue-generating apps worldwide, 500,000 couples globally. That's not a workplace. That's a launchpad.
        </p>
        <p>
          So I did what any growth marketer worth their salt would do. I didn't apply. <strong>I demonstrated.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- EPILOGUE: WHY THE TIMING IS RIGHT -->
  <section class="spoke-section">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-6">
        This Proposal <span class="text-sage">IS</span> My Resume.
      </h2>
      <div class="text-left max-w-3xl mx-auto prose-story">
        <p>
          I didn't apply for this position the normal way because I don't think the normal way is the best way. I built an entire product proposal — market analysis, competitive landscape, financial model, brand identity — because that's what I'd do if I already had the job.
        </p>
        <p>
          Everything in my life has been pointing to this moment.
        </p>
        <p>
          I was born in Zimbabwe, raised to adapt. I learned marketing in the trenches — not from a textbook, but from fifteen years of campaigns that worked and campaigns that didn't. I wrote three products that taught me more about market fit than any MBA. I handwritten sales letters to internalize the craft of copywriting. I dove deeper into AI than most people in marketing ever will — not because I had to, but because I'm <em>technically curious</em> and I can't help myself.
        </p>
        <p>
          Behind all of this is my family. My partner, who holds down the fort while I work night shifts and chase this dream. My kids, who are the reason I get up before dawn. My retired parents, who I support. Everything I do is for them. Every risk I take, every late night, every project — it's all building toward a life where I can provide for the people I love while doing work that actually matters.
        </p>
        <p>
          Cupla isn't just a job listing I found on SEEK. It's the opportunity I've been training for my whole life — I just didn't know it until I saw it. The recurring dream was right: <strong>you have to be ready when the game starts.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm ready.
        </p>
        <p class="text-center">
          I don't just want a position. I want to build <strong>this</strong>. And I just proved I can.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row justify-center gap-4 mt-10">
        <a href="/proposal/" class="btn-primary">&larr; Back to the Full Proposal</a>
        <a href="/proposal/#deep-dive" class="btn-secondary">Explore the Data</a>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 pt-8 border-t border-border">
        <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row items-center justify-center gap-4 sm:gap-6">
          <div class="flex-shrink-0">
            <div class="w-36 h-36 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border-2 border-sage/30 shadow-md">
              <img src="/images/team/barry-full.png" alt="Barry Grottis" class="w-full h-full object-cover" />
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="text-center sm:text-left">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-text-primary mb-1">Barry Grottis</h3>
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary max-w-sm">
              Born in Zimbabwe. 15 years in digital marketing. SEO, paid acquisition, product development, direct response copywriting, and AI-powered builds. Every failure was a lesson. Every lesson was training. Every bit of it led here.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ProposalLayout>

<style>
  .prose-story {
    @apply text-text-secondary leading-relaxed;
  }
  .prose-story p {
    @apply mb-5 text-base;
  }
  .prose-story strong {
    @apply text-text-primary font-semibold;
  }
  .prose-story em {
    @apply italic text-text-primary;
  }
</style>